<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-721-998  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 721 998.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Oct 2 1989 n239 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The fiber of the intra-city; small network suppliers offer cheapalternatives to telcos. (telephone companies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Myers, Kara.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Less expensive transmission costs, superior reliability andadditional features are convincing financial businesses in largemetropolitan areas to switch from Regional Bell Holding Companies(RBOC) to fiber-optic network carriers.andP;  Metropolitan FiberSystems, which offers network services at 15 percent below whatRBOCs charge, has fiber-optic networks in San Francisco, Chicago,Boston, Baltimore, Minneapolis and Philadelphia.andP;  The companyplans to have networks operating in Los Angeles and Houston by theend of 1989.andP;  Cost savings are not the only attractive feature offiber-optic networks: redundancy features, which reroute networktraffic in the event of disabled cable, are particularly importantto companies that rely heavily on telecommunications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc. (management).andO;Topic:     Bell Regional Holding CompaniesFiber OpticsMetropolitan Area NetworksTelephone CompaniesCompetition.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>